Objective:¶

To understand and gain insights from a retail dataset by performing various exploratory data analyses, data visualization, and data modelling.

Dataset Columns:¶

  • InvoiceNo: Invoice number. A unique number per invoice.
  • StockCode: Product code. A unique number per product.
  • Description: Product description.
  • Quantity: The number of products sold per invoice.
  • InvoiceDate: The date and time of the invoice.
  • UnitPrice: The price of one unit of the product.
  • CustomerID: Customer identification number.
  • Country: The country where the customer resides.

In [31]:

Out[31]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Total Sales')

observations: Peaks: There are several peaks in sales, exceeding $80,000. These likely correspond to high-demand periods or special events.

Troughs: Some points drop near zero, indicating low sales. These could be seasonal lulls or specific downtimes. Seasonal Trends: The graph suggests seasonal fluctuations in sales. For instance: December and January show higher sales (holiday season). Summer months (June, July, and August) exhibit lower sales.

4.4. Plot a heatmap to display the correlation between numeric columns.

In [33]:
#  Heatmap of correlation between numeric columns
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
numeric_columns = new_data.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns
correlation_matrix = new_data[numeric_columns].corr()
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Columns')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Quantity vs. TotalPrice:

Here, we see a strong positive correlation (0.9). As the quantity of items sold increases, the total price tends to increase as well in a linear fashion. More sales lead to higher total revenue.

However, Surprisingly the Unit Price of an item doesn't seem to affect the quantity of that item that is purchased.

from mlxtend.frequent_patterns import apriori, association_rules

# Creating a basket
basket = (data.groupby(['InvoiceNo', 'Description'])['Quantity']
          .sum().unstack().reset_index().fillna(0)
          .set_index('InvoiceNo'))

# Convert the units to 1 hot encoded values
def encode_units(x):
    if x <= 0:
        return 0
    if x >= 1:
        return 1

basket_encoded = basket.applymap(encode_units)

# Build frequent items
frequent_itemsets = apriori(basket_encoded, min_support=0.03, use_colnames=True)

# Association rules
rules = association_rules(frequent_itemsets, metric="lift", min_threshold=1)

# Plot rolling average
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

plt.plot(daily_sales_rolling, label='7-Day Rolling Average', color='red')

plt.legend()

# Calculate z-scores to detect anomalies
daily_sales_mean = daily_sales.mean()
daily_sales_std = daily_sales.std()
daily_sales_zscore = (daily_sales - daily_sales_mean) / daily_sales_std

# Define threshold for anomaly (e.g., z-score > 3 or < -3)
threshold = 3
anomalies = daily_sales_zscore[(daily_sales_zscore > threshold) | (daily_sales_zscore < -threshold)]

# Plot anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(daily_sales, label='Daily Sales')
plt.scatter(anomalies.index, anomalies, color='red', label='Anomalies', zorder=5)
plt.title('Anomalies Detected in Sales Data')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

7 - day rolling Average¶

Daily Sales (blue line): The blue line shows raw daily sales data, which fluctuate heavily over time. There are several visible spikes and dips throughout the year, suggesting potential anomalies where sales deviate significantly from the normal trend.

7-Day Rolling Average (red line): The red line, representing the 7-day rolling average, smooths out these fluctuations to give a more stable view of the overall sales trend. When analyzing anomalies, the rolling average helps highlight persistent deviations that may indicate genuine sales trends rather than temporary outliers caused by noise.

Anomalies Detection Insights: Early 2011: In the beginning, there’s a sharp spike in sales followed by a significant drop. The rolling average captures this initial anomaly as a steep decline, likely following a post-holiday sales peak. Low Sales Period: From February to May, sales appear lower overall. While there are some daily fluctuations, the rolling average maintains a consistent lower value. Sales anomalies in this period would be rare or indicate abnormally low sales.

Late 2011 (September-December): The rolling average shows a gradual rise, especially in the last quarter of the year, indicating a buildup to a major event (likely holiday sales). Anomalies here are likely tied to the extreme spike seen toward the end of the year

Z - Score Anomalies:¶

Interpretation: Daily Sales (blue line): The blue line represents the daily sales over time, showing fluctuations in sales values from around 2011 to late 2011. There are noticeable peaks and valleys, with sales spiking significantly at certain points.

Anomalies (red dots): The red dots mark the sales data points that have been identified as anomalies, meaning these points deviate significantly from the average trend. Interpretation:¶

Support (X-axis): Represents the proportion of transactions that contain the itemset in the rule. A support value of around 0.0315 (3.15%) means that the itemset appears in 3.15% of the transactions.

Confidence (Y-axis): Indicates the likelihood that the consequent of the rule is purchased when the antecedent is purchased. Higher confidence values (around 0.75) suggest strong reliability in the association.

Lift (Bubble Size): The size of the bubbles represents the lift. Lift quantifies how much more likely the consequent is purchased when the antecedent is purchased, compared to random chance.

A lift greater than 1 shows a positive association between the products. In your case, lift values range from about 7.91 to 17.35, meaning the likelihood of buying one product increases 7 to 17 times when the antecedent products are purchased.

Interpretation of above graph:

  1. Support (X-axis): The support is approximately 0.032, meaning these itemsets appear in around 3.2% of transactions. This is a relatively common itemset or rule within your dataset.
  2. Confidence (Y-axis): There are two points, one with a confidence close to 0.65 (65%) and another closer to 0.40 (40%). This suggests that for one rule, 65% of the time when the antecedent is purchased, the consequent is also purchased, indicating a fairly strong association. The other rule has a lower confidence of 40%, showing a weaker, but still notable, association between the antecedent and consequent.
  3. Lift (Bubble Size): The single label shows the lift of one rule: 8.39. A lift of 8.39 means that the items in this rule are 8.39 times more likely to be bought together than if they were bought independently. This indicates a strong association between the items in this rule.

Summary: Two rules in this plot. One has high confidence (approx. 65%) and a lift of 8.39, meaning it is both a strong and reliable rule. The other rule has lower confidence (approx. 40%) but may still be useful depending on your business goals. 14. Product Recommendation Systems:¶

  • Develop a system to recommend products to users.
  • Consider collaborative filtering techniques, matrix factorization, or deep learning-based approaches like neural collaborative filtering.
In [58]:
# Create a user-product matrix
user_product_matrix = data.pivot_table(index='CustomerID', columns='StockCode', values='Quantity', fill_value=0)
reindexed_user_product_matrix = user_product_matrix.reset_index()
# Compute the cosine similarity matrix
cosine_sim = cosine_similarity(user_product_matrix)

# Get product recommendations for a user based on their purchase history
def get_recommendations(user_id, cosine_sim=cosine_sim):
    idx = reindexed_user_product_matrix[reindexed_user_product_matrix['CustomerID']==user_id].index[0]        
    # Get pairwise similarity scores
    sim_scores = list(enumerate(cosine_sim[idx]))
    
    # Sort users based on similarity scores
    sim_scores = sorted(sim_scores, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    # Get products bought by the most similar user
    user_idx = sim_scores[1][0]
    similar_user_products = user_product_matrix.iloc[user_idx]
    recommended_products = similar_user_products[similar_user_products > 0].index.tolist()
    
    return recommended_products

stockcodelist = get_recommendations(13113.0) # Replace 2154 with an actual CustomerID
print(f"Stockcode list for recommended products are - {stockcodelist}")

# For this example, let's assume if a customer hasn't purchased in the last 6 months, they've churned
new_data['LastPurchase'] = new_data.groupby('CustomerID')['InvoiceDate'].transform('max')
max_date = new_data['InvoiceDate'].max()
new_data['Churn'] = (max_date - new_data['LastPurchase']).dt.days > 180

X = new_data[['TotalPrice', 'Quantity']] # Add more relevant features
y = new_data['Churn']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

clf = LogisticRegression()
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Interpretation:¶

Model Performance Metrics:

  1. For Non-Churned Customers (False): Precision: 0.96 The model correctly classifies 96% of the non-churned customers. This is a good performance for this class. Recall: 1.00 The model identifies 100% of non-churned customers correctly, meaning it doesn’t miss any non-churned customers. F1-Score: 0.98 The F1-score, a balanced measure of precision and recall, is very high, confirming strong performance in identifying non-churned customers.

  2. For Churned Customers (True): Precision: 0.00 The model is not correctly predicting any churned customers, meaning when the model predicts a customer has churned, it's wrong 100% of the time. Recall: 0.00 The model is failing to identify any of the actual churned customers, meaning none of the customers who have churned are being caught by the model. F1-Score: 0.00 The F1-score is 0 because both precision and recall for the churned class are 0, confirming that the model is unable to handle this class at all.

  3. Overall Metrics: Accuracy: 0.96 While the model has high accuracy (96%), this metric is misleading because the dataset is imbalanced. Most customers are non-churned, so the model simply predicting "non-churned" for almost all customers gives high accuracy, but doesn't mean the model is performing well overall. Macro Average (avg): Precision: 0.48, Recall: 0.50, F1-Score: 0.49 The macro average shows that, on average, the model’s performance across both classes is very poor. These low scores reflect the model's failure to predict the churned customers. Weighted Average (avg): Precision: 0.92, Recall: 0.96, F1-Score: 0.94 The weighted average is heavily influenced by the majority class (non-churned customers), which makes it look better than the macro average. This shows that the model is performing well for the majority class but poorly for the minority (churned) class.

Key Insight: The model still cannot detect churned customers at all (0 precision and recall for the churned class). This is a classic case of a model being biased toward the majority class (non-churned customers). The high accuracy is deceptive because the model is not doing well in predicting churned customers, which is the goal.

The model isn’t learning to distinguish between churned and non-churned customers well. The True Churn class (customers who have churned) is likely a minority class, and the model is biased towards predicting the majority class (not churned).

  • For any given machine learning model you use, apply techniques like grid search or random search for hyperparameter tuning.
  • Use ensemble methods (e.g., stacking, bagging, boosting) to enhance prediction performance.

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100],
    'penalty': ['l2']
}

grid = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(), param_grid, verbose=3)
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(grid.best_params_)

grid_predictions = grid.predict(X_test)
print(classification_report(y_test, grid_predictions))
